        <header>
            <h1>The Tasty History of Pizza</h1>
        </header>
        <section>
            <h1>Ancient Beginning</h1>
            <img id="img" src="https://thumbs.dreamstime.com/z/piping-hot-pizza-its-melted-cheese-irresistible-aromas-solution-to-any-voracious-desire-delicious-282168727.jpg" alt="Delicious Pizza" width="300px"> 
            <p>Long before modern pizza, ancient Egyptians, Greeks, and Romans baked flatbreads topped with olive oil, herbs, and cheese.
                These early dishes were simple, yet they inspired what we now call pizza!</p>   
            <h1>It's Birthplace: Naples, Italy</h1>
            
                <p>
                  In the 1700s, the people of Naples began adding tomatoes to flatbread, creating the earliest version of modern pizza.
                  It quickly became a favorite among the working class as a cheap and delicious meal.
                </p><img id="img" src="https://img.freepik.com/premium-photo/create-detailed-handdrawn-illustration-delicious-pizza-with-all-its-mouthwatering-toppings_388313-2175.jpg
                " alt="Delicious Pizza" width="300px"> 
            <h1>The Margherita Pizza</h1>
                <p>
                  In 1889, Queen Margherita of Savoy visited Naples and tried the local pizza. 
                  To honor her, a local chef created the Margherita pizza, topped with tomatoes, mozzarella cheese, and basil to represent the colors of the Italian flag.
                </p>
            <h1>Pizza's Journey to America</h1>
                <p>Italian immigrants brought pizza to America in the early 1900s. The first U.S. pizzeria opened in New York in 1905.
                    After World War II, pizza exploded in popularity around the globe—with new toppings, crusts, and styles in every country. </p>
        </section>
